<gco:CharacterString>Idaho 2008 305(b) & 303(d) Integrated Report - Water Quality. Every two years, DEQ is required by the federal Clean Water Act to conduct a comprehensive analysis of Idaho's water bodies to determine whether they meet state water quality standards and support beneficial uses or if additional pollution controls are needed. This analysis is summarized in an "Integrated Water Quality Monitoring and Assessment Report" (Integrated Report), which is submitted to the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) for approval. The report serves as a guide for developing and implementing water quality improvement plans (total maximum daily loads, or TMDLs) to protect water quality and achieve federal and state water quality standards.</gco:CharacterString>          </gmd:abstract>          <gmd:purpose>             <gco:CharacterString>The Integrated Report serves three functions. First, it is a reporting requirement of the Clean Water Act, so DEQ must prepare an Integrated Report to be in compliance with federal law. Second, it provides the public the opportunity to learn about and comment on the status of all of Idaho's waters. Third, the Integrated Report compiles environmental data and information from all components of DEQ's surface water quality program, as well as from other agencies, organizations, and individuals, which gives water quality managers a comprehensive look at the relative quality of all of Idaho's water bodies and helps them to set priorities and allocate resources accordingly.</gco:CharacterString>          </gmd:purpose>          <gmd:credit>             <gco:CharacterString>ID DEQ, EPA, Research Triangle Institute, USGS-NHD Program</gco:CharacterString>
